  "local_port": 47892,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do I make Pani puri chutney in Tamil Nadu style?",
  "response": "Pani Puri, also known as Golgappa or Puchka, is a popular street food in India, and the chutneys are a crucial part of its flavor. In Tamil Nadu, the pani puri chutney often has a unique regional twist, focusing on tangy, spicy, and sweet flavors. Here\u2019s how you can make **Tamil Nadu-style Pani Puri chutney**:\n\n---\n\n### **Ingredients for Green Chutney (Coriander-Pudina Chutney):**\n1. Fresh coriander leaves \u2013 1 cup (tightly packed)  \n2. Fresh mint leaves (pudina) \u2013 \u00bd cup  \n3. Green chilies \u2013 2-3 (adjust to taste)  \n4. Ginger \u2013 1-inch piece  \n5. Lemon juice \u2013 1 tbsp  \n6. Salt \u2013 to taste  \n7. Water \u2013 as needed for blending  \n\n---\n\n### **Method for Green Chutney:**\n1. Wash the coriander leaves, mint leaves, and green chilies thoroughly.  \n2. In a blender, add coriander, mint, green chilies, ginger, salt, and a little water.  \n3. Blend into a smooth paste. Add water as needed to achieve the desired consistency.  \n4. Add lemon juice and mix well.  \n5. Store in an airtight container and refrigerate until serving.  \n\n---\n\n### **Ingredients for Sweet Tamarind Chutney (Imli Chutney):**\n1. Tamarind \u2013 4 tbsp (seedless and soaked in warm water for 20 minutes)  \n2. Jaggery \u2013 \u00bd cup (grated or powdered)  \n3. Red chili powder \u2013 \u00bd tsp  \n4. Cumin powder \u2013 \u00bd tsp  \n5. Salt \u2013 to taste  \n6. Water \u2013 as needed  \n\n---\n\n### **Method for Sweet Tamarind Chutney:**\n1. Squeeze the soaked tamarind to extract its pulp. Strain to remove any fibers.  \n2. In a pan, add the tamarind pulp, jaggery, red chili powder, cumin powder, and salt.  \n3. Cook on medium heat, stirring continuously until the jaggery dissolves and the mixture thickens slightly.  \n4. Remove from heat and let it cool.  \n5. Store in an airtight container and refrigerate.  \n\n---\n\n### **Ingredients for Spicy Pani (Water)**:  \n1. Mint leaves (pudina) \u2013 1 cup  \n2. Coriander leaves \u2013 1 cup  \n3. Green chilies \u2013 3-4  \n4. Ginger \u2013 1-inch piece  \n5. Black salt (kala namak) \u2013 1 tsp  \n6. Cumin powder \u2013 1 tsp  \n7. Chaat masala \u2013 1 tsp  \n8. Lemon juice \u2013 2 tbsp  \n9. Salt \u2013 to taste  \n10. Water \u2013 2 cups  \n\n---\n\n### **Method for Spicy Pani**:  \n1. Blend mint leaves, coriander leaves, green chilies, and ginger into a smooth paste using water.  \n2. Strain the mixture to remove fibrous bits.  \n3. Add black salt, cumin powder, chaat masala, lemon juice, and salt. Mix well.  \n4. Add 2 cups of water and adjust the seasoning as per taste.  \n5. Chill in the refrigerator before serving.  \n\n---\n\n### **Assembling Pani Puri**:\n1. Make a small hole in the puri (fried hollow shells).  \n2. Fill with boiled and mashed potatoes, boiled chana (optional), and a pinch of salt.  \n3. Add a spoonful of green chutney and sweet tamarind chutney inside the puri.  \n4. Dip the puri into the spicy pani and enjoy immediately!\n\n---\n\nThis Tamil Nadu-style Pani Puri chutney recipe will give you a burst of flavors typical of the region. Adjust the spice and sweetness levels to suit your taste! \ud83d\ude0a",
  "temperature": 1.0,
